VALUES
(1, 36, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'children of Dishon', 18, 36, 'theology', 'The Importance of Heritage', 'This passage suggests that the descendants of Dishon, like others in genealogies, illustrate God''s commitment to preserving a remnant through familial lines. Many scholars believe genealogies serve not only as historical records but also as a reminder of God''s faithfulness across generations. They demonstrate how God employs individual families to fulfill His divine purposes.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Hemdan, and Eshban, and Ithran, and Cheran.', 38, 81, 'question', 'Reflecting on Legacy', 'In considering the names ''Hemdan, Eshban, Ithran, and Cheran,'' what do these names represent in terms of legacy and identity for future generations? How might understanding these names deepen your appreciation for the lineage of God''s people?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'The children of Ezer are these; Bilhan, and Zaavan, and Akan.', 0, 61, 'connection', 'Ezer''s Lineage Connection', 'The mention of Ezer and his children, Bilhan, Zaavan, and Akan, connects to 1 Chronicles 1:42, which lists the descendants of Esau. This highlights the continuity of family lines from Genesis to Chronicles and reinforces the importance of genealogies in Scripture, emphasizing God''s faithfulness to His promises across generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Chronicles 1:42", "description": "Lists the descendants of Esau, illustrating the continuity of Ezer''s lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Ezer', 16, 20, 'greek', 'Ezer''s Meaning', 'אֵצֶר (Ezer, H5828) - helper, support. The name Ezer means ''helper'' and reflects the role of individuals in the biblical narrative, showcasing how family members support one another in fulfilling God’s purposes.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5828", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning helper."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'Bilhan, and Zaavan, and Akan.', 32, 61, 'theology', 'Significance of Names', 'Many scholars believe that the names Bilhan, Zaavan, and Akan may hold cultural significance in understanding the identity and roles of these descendants within the broader narrative of Israel''s history. Names often reflect character or destiny in the biblical context, suggesting that the legacies of these individuals may play a role in the unfolding story of God’s people.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'The children of Ezer are these;', 0, 31, 'question', 'What Does Lineage Mean?', 'What does it mean to be part of a lineage that signifies God''s promises? How does understanding our spiritual heritage influence our identity and purpose today?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'The children of Dishan are these; Uz, and Aran.', 0, 47, 'connection', 'Connection to Other Nations', 'The names Uz and Aran appear in other biblical contexts. Uz is notably connected to Job, as Job 1:1 mentions a man from the land of Uz. This connection enriches our understanding of the descendants of Dishan, suggesting a lineage that may have influenced or interacted with significant biblical figures. Aran is also mentioned in Genesis 22:21 as a descendant of Nahor, indicating a broader family network. Understanding these connections highlights the interwoven narratives of Genesis.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Job 1:1", "description": "Job''s origin from the land of Uz."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 22:21", "description": "Aran''s mention as a descendant of Nahor."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'The children of Dishan are these; Uz, and Aran.', 0, 47, 'theology', 'Significance of Lineage', 'This verse illustrates the importance of genealogy in Scripture, as it not only records names but also serves to establish the heritage and identity of nations. Many scholars believe that genealogies reinforce God''s covenant promises through specific lineages, demonstrating His faithfulness across generations. The descendants mentioned here contribute to the broader narrative of God’s unfolding plan through familial lines.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'Uz, and Aran.', 34, 47, 'question', 'Understanding Names', 'What might the names Uz and Aran signify in terms of their character or destiny as descendants of Dishan? Considering that names in the biblical context often carry deeper meanings, how can understanding these names help us reflect on the legacy we leave behind in our own lives?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'These are the dukes that came of the Horites;', 0, 45, 'connection', 'Dukes of Edom and Historical Context', 'The mention of the dukes from the Horites connects to Genesis 14:6, where the Horites are described as inhabitants of Seir. This relationship highlights the historical context of Edom and its rulers, as it shows the lineage and governance that existed prior to Israel''s establishment as a nation. Understanding this lineage enriches our grasp of the biblical narrative and God''s unfolding plan through different peoples.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 14:6", "description": "References the Horites and their territory."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'duke Lotan, duke Shobal, duke Zibeon, duke Anah,', 46, 94, 'theology', 'Significance of Dukes in Governance', 'The listing of dukes emphasizes the structure of leadership and governance in ancient societies. Many scholars believe that these titles reflect a form of tribal leadership that was significant in maintaining social order. This suggests that God''s sovereignty extends over nations and tribes, highlighting His involvement in the rise and fall of rulers, as seen later in the history of Israel.', 'figure.mind.and.body', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the implications of tribal leadership in biblical history."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'These are the dukes that came of the Horites;', 0, 45, 'question', 'Understanding Tribal Lineage', 'What does the establishment of dukes and tribal leaders in Edom reveal about God''s plan for governance in human societies? How might this influence our understanding of leadership and authority in our own lives?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'duke Lotan, duke Shobal, duke Zibeon, duke Anah,', 46, 94, 'greek', 'Duke in Leadership Context', 'Though the original text is in Hebrew, the concept of ''duke'' can be related to the Greek term ἄρχων (archon, G758), which means ruler or leader. This term signifies authority and governance, akin to the role of the dukes listed here, reflecting the hierarchical structure of leadership within a community.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G758", "description": "Strong''s number for ''archon'', relating to rulers."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'Duke Dishon, duke Ezer, duke Dishan: these are the dukes that came of Hori, among their dukes in the land of Seir.', 0, 114, 'connection', 'Edom''s Leadership', 'The mention of ''dukedoms'' in Genesis 36:30 connects to Genesis 14:1-2, where we see the concept of kings and rulers emerging in the ancient Near East. This connection highlights the political structure within Edom and contrasts it with Israel''s future monarchy, emphasizing God''s sovereignty in establishing leadership. Understanding these backgrounds can deepen our appreciation for the significance of kingship in biblical history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 14:1", "description": "Describes the early emergence of kings in the region."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'Duke Dishon, duke Ezer, duke Dishan: these are the dukes that came of Hori, among their dukes in the land of Seir.', 0, 114, 'theology', 'Divine Sovereignty', 'This verse suggests that God''s providence orchestrates the establishment of various leaders and nations, including the Edomites. Many scholars believe this reflects God''s control over the rise and fall of nations, as evidenced in Romans 13:1, where it is stated that all governing authorities are established by God. This reinforces the belief that God is actively involved in human history, guiding it according to His divine plan.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Romans 13:1", "description": "Discusses God''s sovereignty over authorities."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'these are the dukes that came of Hori, among their dukes in the land of Seir.', 37, 114, 'question', 'Understanding Heritage', 'What does it mean for the Edomites to have distinct dukes and lineage as ''the dukes that came of Hori''? How does this understanding of heritage and identity shape our view of community in our own lives? Reflecting on the importance of lineage can lead to a deeper appreciation of our own spiritual heritage and connection within the body of Christ.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'the kings that reigned in the land of Edom', 14, 56, 'connection', 'Edom''s Historical Context', 'This phrase connects to 1 Samuel 8:5, where Israel demands a king like other nations. The reference to Edom''s kings highlights the contrast between Israel''s eventual monarchy and the established rule in Edom. This emphasizes God''s unique covenant with Israel and the significance of their identity as a nation ruled by divine law rather than human kingship.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 8:5", "description": "Israel asks for a king, contrasting their governance with Edom''s."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'before there reigned any king over the children of Israel', 58, 115, 'theology', 'God as Sovereign King', 'This passage suggests that God''s kingship preceded human governance. Many scholars believe this highlights the sovereignty of God over His people, establishing that their identity and purpose are rooted in divine authority rather than human systems. It invites reflection on who truly reigns in our lives today.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'kings that reigned in the land of Edom', 18, 56, 'question', 'Understanding Leadership', 'What does it mean for a nation to have kings ruling before God''s chosen people did? How does this historical precedence influence our understanding of leadership in the church and society today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'before there reigned any king over the children of Israel', 58, 115, 'greek', 'Original Language Insight', 'מֶלֶךְ (melech, H4428) - king, ruler, sovereign. This Hebrew term conveys authority and governance, establishing the concept of kingship that is central to understanding both Edom''s political structure and Israel''s covenant relationship with God, who ultimately is their true King.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4428", "description": "Strong''s number for ''king'' in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'Bela the son of Beor', 4, 24, 'connection', 'Connection to Balaam', 'The name ''Bela'' may remind readers of Balaam, a significant figure in Numbers who was also a son of Beor (Numbers 22:5). This connection emphasizes the importance of the lineage and the potential impact of these individuals on Israel''s history. Balaam''s story illustrates the complexity of divine purpose and human agency, making the mention of Bela particularly poignant as it relates to God''s unfolding plan.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Numbers 22:5", "description": "Balaam, son of Beor, is a well-known prophet whose actions significantly impacted Israel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'reigned in Edom', 25, 40, 'theology', 'The Sovereignty of God', 'This phrase highlights God''s sovereignty over nations and rulers. Many scholars believe that the mention of kings in Edom before Israel''s monarchy underscores God''s control over history and His plans for Israel. The existence of a ruling structure in Edom serves as a backdrop to Israel''s own eventual kingship, illustrating the divine orchestration of events.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Waltke, Bruce K. Genesis: A Commentary.", "description": "Waltke discusses God''s sovereignty over the nations in the context of Israel''s development."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'the name of his city was Dinhabah', 46, 79, 'question', 'Significance of Place Names', 'What does the naming of Dinhabah reveal about identity and legacy? In the ancient Near Eastern context, names often held significant meaning and were tied to the character or destiny of the place or people. Reflecting on this, how might the names we give today shape our understanding of community and heritage?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'Bela died, and Jobab', 4, 24, 'connection', 'Leadership Transition', 'The transition of leadership from Bela to Jobab reflects the biblical theme of succession and divine sovereignty in governance. This pattern can be compared to 1 Samuel 10:1, where Saul is anointed king, marking a significant shift in Israel''s leadership. Such transitions illustrate God''s control over who leads His people, pointing to the necessity of divine appointment in authority.', 'arrow.triangle.branch', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 10:1", "description": "Saul''s anointing highlights God''s role in establishing leaders."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'the son of Zerah of Bozrah', 25, 51, 'greek', 'Significance of Names', 'Though this passage is in Hebrew, the name ''Jobab'' can be linked to the Hebrew root ''יָבַב'' (yabav, H3036), meaning ''to cry out'' or ''to shout.'' The meanings of names often carry significance in biblical narratives, suggesting that Jobab''s reign could symbolize a time of calling out to God or seeking His guidance in leadership.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3036", "description": "Root meaning related to Jobab''s name."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'Jobab the son of Zerah', 19, 41, 'theology', 'God''s Covenant and Nations', 'This verse illustrates the formation of nations and their leaders outside of Israel, emphasizing God''s sovereignty over all peoples. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader theological theme of God''s covenant extending beyond Israel to encompass all nations, as seen in Genesis 12:3, where Abraham''s descendants are promised to be a blessing to all families of the earth.', 'figure.mind.and.body', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:3", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham regarding all nations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 33, 33, 'kjv', 'died, and Jobab', 9, 24, 'question', 'What Does Leadership Death Mean?', 'What does the death of Bela signify in the context of leadership and God''s plan for Edom? How might this event encourage us to reflect on the temporality of human authority and the importance of seeking God''s guidance in times of transition?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 34, 34, 'kjv', 'And Jobab died, and Husham of the land of Temani reigned in his stead.', 0, 70, 'connection', 'Leadership Succession', 'The transition of leadership in this verse parallels the cycle of kingship seen in 1 Samuel 8:7, where God instructs Samuel to heed the people''s request for a king, indicating God''s involvement in the governance of His people. This connection underscores the theme of divine sovereignty in leadership choices throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 8:7", "description": "God''s instruction to Samuel regarding kingship"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 34, 34, 'kjv', 'Jobab died', 4, 14, 'theology', 'The Nature of Mortality', 'This passage suggests the inevitability of death, a recurring theme in Scripture that reminds believers of human frailty and the temporality of earthly power. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical teaching on mortality and its implications for understanding life, legacy, and the hope of resurrection.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 3:19", "description": "The curse of mortality due to sin"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 34, 34, 'kjv', 'in his stead', 57, 69, 'question', 'Understanding Succession', 'What does the phrase ''in his stead'' reveal about the nature of leadership and succession in our lives? How can we reflect on the idea of being replaced or succeeded in our roles and responsibilities?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 35, 35, 'kjv', 'who smote Midian in the field of Moab', 45, 82, 'connection', 'Connection to Numbers 31', 'The phrase references Hadad''s military victory over Midian, which connects to Numbers 31:1-2, where Moses is commanded to take vengeance on the Midianites. This victory is significant in the context of Israel''s interactions with neighboring nations and highlights God''s judgment and deliverance through chosen leaders.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Numbers 31:1", "description": "God commands Moses to take vengeance on the Midianites."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 35, 35, 'kjv', 'the name of his city was Avith', 110, 140, 'theology', 'Significance of City Names', 'The naming of cities in the Bible often reflects their significance or the character of the leader. Many scholars believe that ''Avith'' could symbolize a place of strength or refuge, reflecting Hadad''s role as a warrior king. This indicates how leaders shape their communities, not only politically but also spiritually.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 35, 35, 'kjv', 'And Husham died, and Hadad', 0, 26, 'question', 'What does leadership entail?', 'Considering the succession of kings, what qualities must a leader possess to guide a people effectively? How do the transitions between leaders inform our understanding of authority, responsibility, and divine appointment in governance?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 35, 35, 'kjv', 'Hadad the son of Bedad', 21, 43, 'greek', 'Hebrew Context of Hadad', 'הֲדַד (Hadad, H1897) - a name meaning ''thunder'' in Hebrew. Hadad is often associated with a storm deity in various ancient Near Eastern cultures, which can add depth to understanding his character as a warrior figure in the biblical narrative.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1897", "description": "Strong''s number for the name Hadad."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 36, 36, 'kjv', 'And Hadad died, and Samlah of Masrekah reigned in his stead.', 0, 60, 'connection', 'Kingship Transition', 'This verse highlights the theme of leadership succession, echoing the pattern seen in 1 Samuel 8:5, where Israel demands a king to lead them. Both passages illustrate the natural human desire for strong leadership and the inevitability of change in governance. Understanding this transition can deepen our appreciation for the dynamics of authority in biblical history.', 'arrow.triangle.swap', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 8:5", "description": "Israel''s request for a king reflects a similar theme of leadership."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 36, 36, 'kjv', 'Samlah of Masrekah', 20, 38, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Leadership', 'Many scholars believe that the succession of kings, including Samlah, underscores God''s sovereignty over nations and rulers. This passage suggests that even in the midst of human authority, God''s ultimate control prevails, reminding believers that He is actively involved in the governance of the world.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s sovereignty in the rise and fall of leaders."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 36, 36, 'kjv', 'Hadad died', 4, 14, 'question', 'Reflections on Mortality', 'What does the death of Hadad convey about the transient nature of earthly power? As we see leaders come and go, how does this inform our understanding of true authority in our lives, especially in relation to Christ''s everlasting kingship?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 37, 37, 'kjv', 'And Samlah died, and Saul of Rehoboth by the river reigned in his stead.', 0, 72, 'connection', 'Leadership Transitions', 'The transition of leadership noted here parallels the leadership changes in Israel, particularly in 1 Samuel 8:5, where the people request a king to lead them like other nations. This connection highlights the theme of succession and divine sovereignty in leadership, as seen throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 8:5", "description": "The Israelites demand a king, reflecting their desire for human leadership."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 37, 37, 'kjv', 'Saul of Rehoboth by the river', 21, 50, 'theology', 'The Symbolism of Rivers', 'Rivers often symbolize abundance and life in Scripture. Saul''s reign ''by the river'' suggests a position of stability and prosperity. Many scholars believe that this geographical detail underscores God''s provision for His people through divinely appointed leaders.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 37, 37, 'kjv', 'And Samlah died,', 0, 16, 'question', 'Understanding Mortality', 'What does the death of leaders like Samlah teach us about the temporality of human authority? How can we find assurance in God''s unchanging nature amidst the changes in leadership around us?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 37, 37, 'kjv', 'Saul of Rehoboth by the river', 21, 50, 'greek', 'Place Names in Context', 'The name ''Rehoboth'' (H7330), meaning ''broad places,'' can signify openness and community. This reflects the notion that God’s chosen leaders often serve in places of growth and expansion.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7330", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew name Rehoboth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 38, 38, 'kjv', 'Baal–hanan the son of Achbor', 19, 47, 'connection', 'Connection to Kingship', 'The name ''Baal-hanan'' is significant in the context of leadership and lineage. It recalls the theme of divine authority in succession. For a broader understanding of kingship and its divine implications, see 1 Samuel 8:5, where Israel asks for a king. This request reflects their desire to conform to surrounding nations, contrasting with God''s intended leadership through judges.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Samuel 8:5", "description": "Israel''s request for a king highlights the importance of divine selection in leadership."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 38, 38, 'kjv', 'And Saul died,', 0, 14, 'theology', 'The Nature of Mortality', 'This passage poignantly underscores the inevitability of death. The transition from one ruler to another reflects the transient nature of earthly power and sovereignty. Many scholars believe this serves as a reminder for believers to focus on the eternal kingdom of God rather than the temporal political structures of this world.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 38, 38, 'kjv', 'Baal–hanan the son of Achbor', 19, 47, 'greek', 'Significance of Names', 'בַּעַל חָנָן (Baal-hanan, H1160) - ''Lord is gracious.'' The name signifies favor and grace, reflecting the hope that accompanies new leadership. Understanding the meanings of biblical names can enrich our grasp of the text''s message.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1160", "description": "Strong''s entry for Baal-hanan, indicating the name''s meaning and significance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 38, 38, 'kjv', 'And Saul died,', 0, 14, 'question', 'Reflection on Leadership', 'What do the deaths of leaders like Saul teach us about the nature of legacy and the impact of one''s life on subsequent generations? How can we apply the lessons of these transitions in our own leadership roles?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 39, 39, 'kjv', 'Baal–hanan the son of Achbor died', 4, 37, 'connection', 'Legacy of Leadership', 'The death of leaders in Scripture often marks significant transitions. In 1 Kings 2:10, we see a similar pattern with the death of David. Both passages reflect the continuity of leadership and the importance of succession, illustrating how God''s plan unfolds through generations. This connection highlights the divine orchestration in the history of Israel.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Kings 2:10", "description": "King David''s death and its implications for succession."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 39, 39, 'kjv', 'the name of his city was Pau', 75, 103, 'theology', 'Significance of Place Names', 'Many scholars believe that the naming of cities in Scripture often reflects the identity and purpose of the people residing there. The name ''Pau'' may signify a place of refuge or safety, aligning with the biblical theme of God providing a space for His people. This suggests that our environments can hold spiritual significance and impact our lives.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 39, 39, 'kjv', 'his wife’s name was Mehetabel', 109, 138, 'greek', 'Biblical Names and Their Meanings', 'מֵהֶתָאֵל (Mehetabel, H4103) - ''God makes well.'' This name conveys a significant theological implication about divine favor and restoration. Names in the Bible often reflect character or destiny, and Mehetabel''s name can be seen as a reminder of God''s providential care over His people.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4103", "description": "Strong''s number for the name Mehetabel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 39, 39, 'kjv', 'the daughter of Matred, the daughter of Mezahab', 140, 187, 'question', 'Understanding Ancestry''s Role', 'What does it mean for Mehetabel to be described as ''the daughter of Matred, the daughter of Mezahab''? How does this lineage influence our understanding of her identity and role in this narrative? Ancestry in biblical texts often bears significance, shaping the story of individuals and their destinies.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 40, 40, 'kjv', 'duke Timnah, duke Alvah, duke Jetheth,', 121, 159, 'connection', 'Esau''s Descendants', 'The mention of ''duke Timnah, duke Alvah, duke Jetheth'' highlights the lineage of Esau, which is detailed further in Genesis 36:11 where it states, ''And the sons of Eliphaz were Teman, Omar, Zepho, and Gatam, and Kenaz.'' This connection shows the significance of Esau''s descendants in the narrative of Israel, emphasizing the broader familial ties and their roles in the region. Also, it relates to the ongoing theme of God''s covenant with Jacob and his descendants versus Esau''s lineage.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 36:11", "description": "Further elaboration on Esau''s descendants."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');